      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a chemical reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars that gives browned food its distinctive flavor. It starts when the temperature of the food increases, typically around 140 to 165 degrees Celsius (284 to 329 degrees Fahrenheit). As the temperature rises, the sugars and amino acids start to react, forming new flavor compounds and browning the food. This process is essential in cooking methods like roasting, grilling, and searing. Keep in mind that the exact temperature range can vary depending on the specific food being cooked and other factors.",
