    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok so caramelization is separate. what about moisture? i noticed that if the surface is too wet the browning takes way longer. does the water somehow interfere with the temperature needed for those reactions to happen?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, moisture can indeed impact the cooking process. Water in the surface of the food tends to boil at 100 degrees Celsius (212 degrees Fahrenheit), which can delay the onset of the Maillard reaction and caramelization. This is because the heat energy is first used to convert the water into steam, rather than directly promoting the chemical reactions that lead to browning. When the surface is dry, heat can more readily reach the necessary temperatures for these reactions to occur, thus resulting in faster browning and flavor development. It's a balancing act – too much moisture can hinder the process, while the right amount can help create a delicious crust.",
      "source": "target",
